# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: new-brunswick-new-jersey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The **119th United States Congress** is the current meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] It convened on January 3, 2025, for the last 17 days of Joe Biden's presidency and continued during the first two years of Donald Trump's second presidency.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Following the 2024 elections, the Republican Party retained its slim majority in the House of Representatives (albeit with losing two net seats to end up with a three-seat majority).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The Republican Party also won a three-seat majority in the Senate after winning four net seats.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Upon Trump's second inauguration on January 20, 2025, the Republican Party has an overall federal government trifecta for the first time since the 115th Congress (2017–2019), which was in session during Trump's first term.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The 119th Congress features the slimmest majority in the House for any party since the 72nd Congress (1931–1933), and the first openly transgender member of Congress in history, Representative Sarah McBride (D-DE).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] It also features the fewest split Senate delegations since the passage of the Seventeenth Amendment, which established the direct election of U.S. senators.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Despite a trifecta, the first year of the Congress saw the lowest number of House votes in a nonelection year since the 101st Congress in 1990.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In the 2024 elections, the Republican Party retained control of the House of Representatives and gained control of the Senate, while Republican nominee Donald Trump won the presidential election, securing a second non-consecutive term.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The results of the election were attributed to economic conditions of voters and concerns over immigration, particularly the Mexico–United States border crisis.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The Senate flipped to a 53–47 Republican majority, and in their leadership elections, Senator John Thune of South Dakota was elected to succeed Mitch McConnell, who had been in power for 18 years.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The House assumed a 220–215 Republican majority, among the narrowest controlling majorities in House history with the 65th Congress.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Mike Johnson was re-elected as speaker on the first ballot after initially not receiving enough votes on the roll call, with the vote remaining open until enough members changed votes to support him.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] On January 6, a joint session convened to count the presidential Electoral College votes.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The proceedings were peaceful, four years after the January 6 Capitol attack, in which supporters of Trump entered the Capitol and disrupted Joe Biden's certification as president.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In response to the attack and Trump's efforts to overturn the 2020 election, Congress has passed revisions to the Electoral Count Act that prevent the vice president from altering the results and significantly raises the bar for certification objections.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The numbers refer to their Senate classes.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] All class 1 seats were contested in the November 2024 elections.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In this Congress, class 1 means their term commenced in the current Congress, requiring re-election in 2030; class 2 means their term ends with this Congress, requiring re-election in 2026; and class 3 means their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 2028.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] All seats were filled by election in November 2024, or special elections thereafter as noted below.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] As of the 2020 United States census, the city's population was 55,266, its highest decennial census count ever and an increase of 85 (+0.2%) from the 2010 census count of 55,181, which in turn reflected an increase of 6,608 (+13.6%) from the 48,573 counted in the 2000 census.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The Census Bureau's Population Estimates Program calculated a population of 57,487 for 2024, making it the 713th-most populous municipality in the nation.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Due to the concentration of medical facilities in the area, including Rutgers Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital and medical school, and Saint Peter's University Hospital, New Brunswick is known as both the *Hub City* and the *Healthcare City*.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The corporate headquarters and production facilities of several global pharmaceutical companies are situated in the city, including Johnson & Johnson and Bristol Myers Squibb.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick is continuing to evolve into a major center for the sciences, arts, and cultural activities.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Downtown New Brunswick is developing a growing skyline, filling with new high-rise towers.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick is noted for its ethnic diversity.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] At one time, one-quarter of the Hungarian population of New Jersey resided in the city, and in the 1930s one out of three city residents was Hungarian.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The Hungarian community continues as a cohesive community, with the 3,200 Hungarian residents accounting for 8% of the population of New Brunswick in 1992.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Growing Asian and Hispanic communities have developed around French Street near Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The area around present-day New Brunswick was first inhabited by the Lenape Native Americans, whose Minisink Trail intersected the Raritan River and followed a route that would be taken by later colonial roads.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The first European settlement at the site of New Brunswick was made in 1681.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] In 1714, the settlement was given the name New Brunswick, after the city of Braunschweig (*Brunswick* in Low German), in the state of Lower Saxony, now located in Germany.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Braunschweig was an influential and powerful city in the Hanseatic League and was an administrative seat for the Duchy of Hanover.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Shortly after the first settlement of New Brunswick in colonial New Jersey, George, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg and Elector of Hanover, became King George I of Great Britain.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Alternatively, the city gets its name from King George II of Great Britain, the Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Centrally located between New York City and Philadelphia along an early thoroughfare known as the *King's Highway* and situated along the Raritan River, New Brunswick became an important hub for Colonial travelers and traders.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick was incorporated as a town in 1736 and chartered as a city in 1784.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] It was incorporated into a town in 1798 as part of the Township Act of 1798.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] It was occupied by the British in the winter of 1776–1777 during the Revolutionary War.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The *Declaration of Independence* received one of its first public readings, by Colonel John Neilson in New Brunswick on July 9, 1776, in the days following its promulgation by the Continental Congress.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] A bronze statue marking the event was dedicated on July 9, 2017, in Monument Square, in front of the Heldrich Hotel.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The Trustees of Queen's College (now Rutgers University), founded in 1766, voted by a margin of ten to seven in 1771 to locate the young college in New Brunswick, selecting the city over Hackensack, in Bergen County, New Jersey.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The Sign of the Red Lion was purchased on behalf of Queens College in 1771, and later sold to the estate of Jacob Rutsen Hardenbergh in 1791.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Classes were held through the American Revolution in various taverns and boarding houses, and at a building known as *College Hall* on George Street, until Old Queens was completed and opened in 1811.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] It remains the oldest building on the Rutgers University campus.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The Queen's College Grammar School (now Rutgers Preparatory School) was established also in 1766, and shared facilities with the college until 1830, when it located in a building (now known as Alexander Johnston Hall) across College Avenue from Old Queens.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] After Rutgers University became the state university of New Jersey in 1945, the Trustees of Rutgers divested itself of Rutgers Preparatory School, which relocated in 1957 to an estate purchased from Colgate-Palmolive in Franklin Township in neighboring Somerset County.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The New Brunswick Theological Seminary, founded in 1784 in New York, moved to New Brunswick in 1810, sharing its quarters with the fledgling Queen's College.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick was formed by royal charter on December 30, 1730, within other townships in Middlesex and Somerset counties and was reformed by royal charter with the same boundaries on February 12, 1763, at which time it was divided into north and south wards.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick was incorporated as a city by an act of the New Jersey Legislature on September 1, 1784.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The existence of an African-American community in New Brunswick dates back to the 18th century, when racial slavery was a part of life in the city and the surrounding area.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Local slaveholders routinely bought and sold African American children, women, and men in New Brunswick in the late-eighteenth and early-nineteenth century.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] In this period, the Market-House was the center of commercial life in the city.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] It was located at the corner of Hiram Street and Queen Street (now Neilson Street) adjacent to the Raritan Wharf.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The site was a place where residents of New Brunswick sold and traded their goods which made it an integral part of the city's economy.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The Market-House also served as a site for regular slave auctions and sales.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] By the late-eighteenth century, New Brunswick became a hub for newspaper production and distribution.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] *The Fredonian*, a popular newspaper, was located less than a block away from the aforementioned Market-House and helped facilitate commercial transactions.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] A prominent part of the local newspapers were sections dedicated to private owners who would advertise their slaves for sale.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The trend of advertising slave sales in newspapers shows that the New Brunswick residents typically preferred selling and buying slaves privately and individually rather than in large groups.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The majority of individual advertisements were for female slaves, and their average age at the time of the sale was 20 years old, which was considered the prime age for childbearing.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Slave owners would get the most profit from the women who fit into this category because these women had the potential to reproduce another generation of enslaved workers.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Additionally, in the urban environment of New Brunswick, there was a high demand for domestic labor, and female workers were preferred for cooking and housework tasks.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The New Jersey Legislature passed An Act for the Gradual Abolition of Slavery in 1804.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Under the provisions of this law, children born to enslaved women after July 4, 1804, would serve their master for a term of 21 years (for girls) or a term of 25 years (for boys), and after this term, they would gain their freedom.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] However, all individuals who were enslaved before July 4, 1804, would continue to be slaves for life and would never attain freedom under this law.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick continued to be home to enslaved African Americans alongside a growing community of free people of color.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The 1810 United States census listed 53 free Blacks and 164 slaves in New Brunswick.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] By the 1810s, some free African Americans lived in a section of the city called Halfpenny Town, which was located along the Raritan River by the east side of the city, near Queen (now Neilson) Street.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Halfpenny Town was a place populated by free blacks as well as poorer whites who did not own slaves.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] This place was known as a social gathering for free blacks that was not completely influenced by white scrutiny and allowed free blacks to socialize among themselves.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] This does not mean that it was free from white eyes and was still under the negative effects of the slavery era.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] In the early decades of the nineteenth century, White and either free or enslaved African Americans shared many of the same spaces in New Brunswick, particularly places of worship.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The First Presbyterian Church, Christ Church, and First Reformed Church were popular among both Whites and Blacks, and New Brunswick was notable for its lack of spaces where African Americans could congregate exclusively.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Most of the time Black congregants of these churches were under the surveillance of Whites.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] That was the case until the creation of the African Association of New Brunswick in 1817.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Both free and enslaved African Americans were active in the establishment of the African Association of New Brunswick, whose meetings were first held in 1817.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The African Association of New Brunswick held a meeting every month, mostly in the homes of free blacks.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Sometimes these meetings were held at the First Presbyterian Church.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Originally intended to provide financial support for the African School of New Brunswick, the African Association grew into a space where blacks could congregate and share ideas on a variety of topics such as religion, abolition and colonization.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Slaves were required to obtain a pass from their owner in order to attend these meetings.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The African Association worked closely with Whites and was generally favored amongst White residents who believed it would bring more racial peace and harmony to New Brunswick.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The African Association of New Brunswick established the African School in 1822.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The African School was first hosted in the home of Caesar Rappleyea in 1823.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The school was located on the upper end of Church Street in the downtown area of New Brunswick about two blocks away from the jail that held escaped slaves.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Both free and enslaved Blacks were welcome to be members of the School.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Reverend Huntington (pastor of the First Presbyterian Church) and several other prominent Whites were trustees of the African Association of New Brunswick.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] These trustees supported the Association which made some slave owners feel safe sending their slaves there by using a permission slip process.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The main belief of these White supporters was that Blacks were still unfit for American citizenship and residence, and some trustees were connected with the American Colonization Society that advocated for the migration of free African Americans to Africa.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The White trustees only attended some of the meetings of the African Association, and the Association was still unprecedented as a space for both enslaved and free Blacks to get together while under minimal supervision by Whites.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The African Association appears to have disbanded after 1824.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] By 1827, free and enslaved Black people in the city, including Joseph and Jane Hoagland, came together to establish the Mount Zion African Methodist Episcopal Church and purchased a plot of land on Division Street for the purpose of erecting a church building.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] This was the first African American church in Middlesex County.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The church had approximately 30 members in its early years.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The church is still in operation and is currently located at 39 Hildebrand Way.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The street Hildebrand Way is named after the late Rev.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Henry Alphonso Hildebrand, who was pastor of Mount Zion AME for 37 years, which is the longest appointment received by a pastor at Mount Zion AME.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Records from the April 1828 census, conducted by the New Brunswick Common Council, state that New Brunswick was populated with 4,435 white residents and 374 free African Americans.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The enslaved population of New Brunswick in 1828 consisted of 57 slaves who must serve for life and 127 slaves eligible for emancipation at age 21 or 25 due to the 1804 Act for the Gradual Abolition of Slavery.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Free and enslaved African Americans accounted for 11% of New Brunswick's population in 1828, a relatively high percentage for New Jersey.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] By comparison, as of the 1830 United States census, African Americans made up approximately 6.4% of the total population of New Jersey.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] In 1824, the New Brunswick Common Council adopted a curfew for free people of color.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Free African Americans were not allowed to be out after 10 pm on Saturday night.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The Common Council also appointed a committee of white residents who were charged with rounding up and detaining free African Americans who appeared to be out of place according to white authorities.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick became a notorious city for slave hunters, who sought to enforce the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Strategically located on the Raritan River, the city was also a vital hub for New Jersey's Underground Railroad.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] For runaway slaves in New Jersey, it served as a favorable route for those heading to New York and Canada.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] When African Americans tried to escape either to or from New Brunswick, they had a high likelihood of getting discovered and captured and sent to New Brunswick's jail, which was located on Prince Street, which by now is renamed Bayard Street.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick has been described as the "most Hungarian city" in the United States, with Hungarian immigrants arriving in the city as early as 1888 and accounting for almost 20 percent of the city's population in 1915.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Hungarians were primarily attracted to the city by employment at Johnson & Johnson factories located in the city.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Hungarians settled mainly in what today is the Fifth Ward and businesses were established to serve the needs of the Hungarian community that were not being met by mainstream businesses.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The immigrant population grew until the end of the immigration boom in the early 20th century.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] During the Cold War, the community was revitalized by the decision to process the tens of thousands of refugees who came to the United States from the failed 1956 Hungarian Revolution at Camp Kilmer, in nearby Edison.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Even though the Hungarian population has been largely supplanted by newer immigrants, there continues to be a Hungarian Festival in the city held on Somerset Street on the first Saturday of June each year; the 44th annual event was held in 2019.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Many Hungarian institutions set up by the community remain and are active in the neighborhood, including Magyar Reformed Church, Ascension Lutheran Church, St.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Several landmarks in the city also testify to its Hungarian heritage.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] There is a street and a park named after Lajos Kossuth, one of the leaders of the Hungarian Revolution of 1848.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The corner of Somerset Street and Plum Street, where the first public statue of Cardinal József Mindszenty was erected, is named Mindszenty Square.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] A stone memorial to the victims of the 1956 Hungarian Revolution stands nearby.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] In the 2010 Census, about 50% of New Brunswick's population is self-identified as Hispanic, the 14th highest percentage among municipalities in New Jersey.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Since the 1960s, many of the new residents of New Brunswick have come from Latin America.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Many citizens moved from Puerto Rico in the 1970s.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] In the 1980s, many immigrated from the Dominican Republic, and still later from Guatemala, Honduras, Ecuador and Mexico.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick is one of nine cities in New Jersey designated as eligible for Urban Transit Hub Tax Credits by the state's Economic Development Authority.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Developers who invest a minimum of $50 million within a half-mile of a train station are eligible for pro-rated tax credit.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick contains a number of examples of urban renewal in the United States.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Johnson & Johnson announced in 1978 that they would remain in New Brunswick and invest $50 million to build a new world headquarters building in the area between Albany Street, Amtrak's Northeast Corridor, Route 18, and George Street, requiring many old buildings and historic roads to be removed.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The Hiram Market area, a historic district that by the 1970s had become a mostly Puerto Rican and Dominican-American neighborhood, was demolished to build a Hyatt hotel and conference center, and upscale housing.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Johnson & Johnson guaranteed the investment made by Hyatt Hotels, as they were wary of building an upscale hotel in a run-down area.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Devco, the hospitals, and the city government have drawn ire from both historic preservationists, those opposing gentrification and those concerned with eminent domain abuses and tax abatements for developers.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick is home to the main campus of Rutgers University and Johnson & Johnson, which in 1983 constructed its new headquarters in the city.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Both work with Devco in a public–private partnership to redevelop downtown, particularly regarding transit-oriented development.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Boraie Development, a real estate development firm based in New Brunswick, has developed projects using the incentives provided by Devco and the state.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Christ Church, originally built in 1742, was the tallest building at the time of construction.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] A steeple was added in 1773 and replaced in 1803.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The six-story First Reformed Church, built in 1812, was long the city's tallest structure.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] One of the earliest tall commercial buildings in the city was the eight-story 112.5 ft (34.29 m) National Bank of New Jersey built in 1908.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The four nine-story 125 ft (38 m) buildings of the New Brunswick Homes housing project, originally built in 1958, were demolished by implosion in 2000 and largely replaced by low-rise housing.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] While there are no buildings over 300 feet (91 meters), since the beginning of the new millennium, a number of high-rise residential buildings have been added to the city's skyline clustered around the New Brunswick station built in the 1960s.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Of the 16 buildings over 150 feet (46 m), nine of them were built in the 21st century; several others are approved or proposed.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city had a total area of 5.75 square miles (14.9 km2), including 5.23 square miles (13.5 km2) of land and 0.52 square miles (1.3 km2) of water (9.06%).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick is on the south side of Raritan Valley along with Piscataway, Highland Park, Edison, and Franklin Township.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick lies southwest of Newark and New York City and northeast of Trenton and Philadelphia.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] While the city does not hold elections based on a ward system it has been so divided.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] There are several neighborhoods in the city, which include the Fifth Ward, Feaster Park, Lincoln Park, Raritan Gardens, and Edgebrook-Westons Mills.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Under the Köppen climate classification, New Brunswick falls within either a hot-summer humid continental climate (*Dfa*) if the 0 °C (32 °F) isotherm is used or a humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*) if the −3 °C (27 °F) isotherm is used.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick has humid, hot summers and moderately cold winters with moderate to considerable rainfall throughout the year.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The average seasonal (October–April) snowfall total is around 29 inches (74 cm).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The average snowiest month is February, which corresponds to the annual peak in nor'easter activity.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] As of the 2020 census, New Brunswick had a population of 55,266.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] 22.2% of residents were under the age of 18 and 6.6% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] For every 100 females there were 100.5 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 98.4 males age 18 and over.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] There were 15,387 households in New Brunswick, of which 36.2% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Of all households, 29.6% were married-couple households, 27.6% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 34.4% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] About 27.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] There were 17,509 housing units, of which 12.1% were vacant.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.7% and the rental vacancy rate was 8.5%.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The 2010 United States census counted 55,181 people, 14,119 households, and 7,751 families in the city.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] There were 15,053 housing units at an average density of 2,879.7 per square mile (1,111.9/km2).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 49.93% (27,553) of the population.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Of the 14,119 households, 31.0% had children under the age of 18; 29.2% were married couples living together; 17.5% had a female householder with no husband present and 45.1% were non-families.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Of all households, 25.8% were made up of individuals and 7.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The average household size was 3.36 and the average family size was 3.91.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] For every 100 females, the population had 105.0 males.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] For every 100 females ages 18 and older there were 105.3 males.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The Census Bureau's 2006–2010 American Community Survey showed that (in 2010 inflation-adjusted dollars) median household income was $44,543 (with a margin of error of +/− $2,356) and the median family income was $44,455 (+/− $3,526).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The per capita income for the borough was $16,395 (+/− $979).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] About 15.5% of families and 25.8% of the population were below the poverty line, including 25.4% of those under age 18 and 16.9% of those age 65 or over.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] As of the 2000 United States census, there were 48,573 people, 13,057 households, and 7,207 families residing in the city.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The population density was 9,293.5 inhabitants per square mile (3,588.2/km2).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] There were 13,893 housing units at an average density of 2,658.1 per square mile (1,026.3/km2).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 51.7% White, 24.5% African American, 1.2% Native American, 5.9% Asian, 0.2% Pacific Islander, 21.0% from other races, and 4.2% from two or more races.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] 39.01% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] There were 13,057 households, of which 29.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 29.6% were married couples living together, 18.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 44.8% were non-families.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] 24.3% of all households were made up of individuals, and 8.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The average household size was 3.23 and the average family size was 3.69.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] For every 100 females, there were 98.4 males.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 96.8 males.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The median household income in the city was $36,080, and the median income for a family was $38,222.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Males had a median income of $25,657 versus $23,604 for females.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The per capita income for the city was $14,308.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] 27.0% of the population and 16.9% of families were below the poverty line.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Out of the total people living in poverty, 25.9% were under the age of 18 and 13.8% were 65 or older.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] City Hall has promoted the nickname "The Health Care City" to reflect the importance of the healthcare industry to its economy.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The city is home to the world headquarters of Johnson & Johnson, along with several medical teaching and research institutions.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Described as the first magnet secondary school program teaching directly affiliated with a teaching hospital and a medical school, New Brunswick Health Sciences Technology High School is a public high school, that operates as part of the New Brunswick Public Schools, focused on health sciences.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Portions of the city are part of an Urban Enterprise Zone (UEZ), one of 32 zones covering 37 municipalities statewide.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick was selected in 2004 as one of two zones added to participate in the program.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] In addition to other benefits to encourage employment and investment within the Zone, shoppers can take advantage of a reduced 3.3125% sales tax rate (half of the 6+5⁄8% rate charged statewide) at eligible merchants.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Established in December 2004, the city's Urban Enterprise Zone status expires in December 2024.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The New Brunswick Performing Arts Center, constructed at a cost of $172 million and topped by 18 stories of apartments, opened in September 2019.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The complex houses three professional venues: Crossroads Theatre (founded in 1978 and focused on the Black American experience), George Street Playhouse (founded in 1974) and the State Theatre (constructed in 1921 for vaudeville and silent films).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The center also houses the American Repertory Ballet (founded in 1963) and the Princeton Ballet School (established in 1954).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] In 1999, the Crossroads Theatre won a Tony Award for Outstanding Regional Theatre.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Crossroads is the first African American theater to receive this honor in the 33-year history of this special award category.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Rutgers University has student-run companies such as Cabaret Theatre, The Livingston Theatre Company, and College Avenue Players which perform everything from musicals to dramatic plays to sketch comedy.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Most recently, Rutgers Opera and Rutgers Symphony Orchestra of Rutgers University Mason-Gross held a performance of *Carmen* in April 2025.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Jersey alt-weeklies *The Aquarian Weekly* and *NJ Indy* cover music and arts in New Brunswick.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick is the site of the Zimmerli Art Museum at Rutgers University (founded in 1966), Albus Cavus, and the Rutgers University Geology Museum (founded in 1872).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick was an important center for avant-garde art in the 1950s–1970s with several artists such as Allan Kaprow, George Segal, George Brecht, Robert Whitman, Robert Watts, Lucas Samaras, Geoffrey Hendricks, Wolf Vostell and Roy Lichtenstein; some of whom taught at Rutgers University.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] This group of artists was sometimes referred to as the "New Jersey School" or the "New Brunswick School of Painting." The *YAM Festival* was a venue on May 19, 1963, for actions and happenings.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] For more information, see Fluxus at Rutgers University.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick's live music scene has been the home to many original rock bands, including some which went on to national prominence such as The Smithereens and Bon Jovi as well as other notable New Brunswick bands.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The city is in particular a center for local punk rock and underground music.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Alternative rock, indie rock, and hardcore music have long been popular in the city's live music scene.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Many alternative rock bands got radio airplay thanks to Matt Pinfield who was part of the New Brunswick music scene for over 20 years at Rutgers University radio WRSU-FM and at alternative rock radio station WHTG-FM.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Local pubs and clubs hosted many local bands, including the Court Tavern and the Melody Bar during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The city was ranked the number 4 spot to see indie bands in New Jersey.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The independent record label Don Giovanni Records originally started to document the New Brunswick basement scene.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] Rutgers radio station WVPH 90.3 FM "The Core" hosts indie music festival "Corefest" on campus.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] A number of jazz organizations and jazz festivals are held in the city, including the Hub City Jazz Festival and the New Brunswick Jazz Project.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The New Brunswick Jazz Project is dedicated to live jazz in the city and surrounding towns.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick also has a plethora of rappers including Trill Lik, Mello B and Amgjay and also GetBizzy Nino.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] New Brunswick is home to a number of film festivals, two of which are presented by the film society, the Rutgers Film Co-op/New Jersey Media Arts Center: the New Jersey Film Festival (1982) and the United States Super 8mm Film + Digital Video Festival (~1988).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The Rutgers Jewish Film Festival was established 1999.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The New Lens Film Festival is an event at the Mason Gross School of the Arts.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] The "Grease trucks" were a group of truck-based food vendors located on the College Avenue Campus at Rutgers.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] They were known for serving "Fat Sandwiches", sub rolls containing fried ingredients.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p01] In 2013, the grease trucks were removed for the construction of a new Rutgers building and moved into various other areas of the Rutgers-New Brunswick Campus.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] New Brunswick City Hall, the New Brunswick Free Public Library, and the New Brunswick Main Post Office are located in the city's Civic Square government district, as are numerous other city, county, state, and federal offices.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The City of New Brunswick is governed within the Faulkner Act, formally known as the Optional Municipal Charter Law, under the Mayor-Council system of municipal government.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The city is one of 71 municipalities (of the 564) statewide governed under this form.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The governing body consists of the Mayor and the five-member City Council, all of whom are elected at-large on a partisan basis to four-year terms of office in even-numbered years as part of the November general election.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The City Council's five members are elected on a staggered basis, with either two or three seats coming up for election every other year and the mayor up for election at the same time that two council seats are up for vote.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] As the legislative body of New Brunswick's municipal government, the City Council is responsible for approving the annual budget, ordinances and resolutions, contracts, and appointments to boards and commissions.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The Council President is elected to a two-year term by the members of the Council at a reorganization meeting held after election and presides over all meetings.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] As of 2026, Democrat James Cahill is the 62nd mayor of New Brunswick; he was sworn in as mayor on January 1, 1991, and is serving a term that expires on December 31, 2026.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Members of the City Council are Council President Manuel J.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Castañeda (D, 2028), Council Vice President Petra N.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Escobar (D, 2026), Matthew Ferguson (D, 2026; elected to serve an unexpired term), Glenn J.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] In January 2024, the city council appointed Matthew Ferguson to fill the seat expiring in December 2026 that had been held by Kevin Egan until he resigned earlier that month to take a seat in the New Jersey General Assembly.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Ferguson served on an interim basis until the November general election, when he was elected to serve the balance of the term of office.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] In January 2023, the City Council expanded from five to seven members.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Gaskins was sworn in as the first Black woman and youngest in history, and Castañeda was elected as the first Latino man.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The New Brunswick Police Department has received attention for various incidents over the years.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] In 1991, the fatal shooting of Shaun Potts, an unarmed black resident, by Sergeant Zane Grey led to multiple local protests.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] In 1996, Officer James Consalvo fatally shot Carolyn "Sissy" Adams, an unarmed prostitute who had bit him.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The Adams case sparked calls for reform in the New Brunswick Police Department, and ultimately was settled with the family.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] James Marshall, were convicted of running a bordello in 2001.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Chinchilla was sentenced to three years and Marshall was sentenced to four.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] In 2011, Officer Brad Berdel fatally shot Barry Deloatch, a black man who had run from police (although police claim he struck officers with a stick); this sparked daily protests from residents.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The current professional city fire department was established in 1914, but the earliest volunteer fire company in the city dates back to 1764.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The department operates out of three stations, with a total of approximately 90 officers and firefighters.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] In 2014, the city received criticism and public attention after fire director Robert Rawls, whose driving record included dozens of accidents and license suspensions, had struck three children in a crosswalk while driving a city-owned vehicle.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] New Brunswick is located in the 6th Congressional District and is part of New Jersey's 17th state legislative district.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] For the 119th United States Congress, New Jersey's 6th congressional district is represented by Frank Pallone (D, Long Branch).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] New Jersey is represented in the United States Senate by Democrats Cory Booker (Newark, term ends 2027) and Andy Kim (Moorestown, term ends 2031).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] For the 2026–2027 session, the 17th legislative district of the New Jersey Legislature is represented in the State Senate by Bob Smith (D, Piscataway) and in the General Assembly by Joseph Danielsen (D, Franklin Township) and Kevin Egan (D, New Brunswick).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Middlesex County is governed by a Board of County Commissioners, whose seven members are elected at-large on a partisan basis to serve three-year terms of office on a staggered basis, with either two or three seats coming up for election each year as part of the November general election.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] At an annual reorganization meeting held in January, the board selects from among its members a commissioner director and deputy director.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Rios (D, Carteret, 2027), Deputy Director Shanti Narra (D, North Brunswick, 2027), Claribel A.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] "Clary" Azcona-Barber (D, New Brunswick, 2025), Charles Kenny (D, Woodbridge Township, 2025), Leslie Koppel (D, Monroe Township, 2026), Chanelle Scott McCullum (D, Piscataway, 2025) and Charles E.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Constitutional officers are: Clerk Nancy Pinkin (D, 2025, East Brunswick), Sheriff Mildred S.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Scott (D, 2025, Piscataway) and Surrogate Claribel Cortes (D, 2026; North Brunswick).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] As of March 23, 2011, there were a total of 22,742 registered voters in New Brunswick, of which 8,732 (38.4%) were registered as Democrats, 882 (3.9%) were registered as Republicans and 13,103 (57.6%) were registered as Unaffiliated.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] There were 25 voters registered to other parties.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] In the 2016 presidential election, Democrat Hillary Clinton received 81.9% of the vote (8,779 cast), ahead of Republican Donald Trump with 14.1% (1,516 votes), and other candidates with 4.0% (426 votes), among the 10,721 ballots cast.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] In the 2008 presidential election, Democrat Barack Obama received 83.3% of the vote (10,717 cast), ahead of Republican John McCain with 14.8% (1,899 votes) and other candidates with 1.1% (140 votes), among the 12,873 ballots cast by the township's 23,533 registered voters, for a turnout of 54.7%.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The New Brunswick Public Schools serve students in pre-kindergarten through twelfth grade.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The district is one of 31 former Abbott districts statewide that were established pursuant to the decision by the New Jersey Supreme Court in *Abbott v.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Burke* which are now referred to as "SDA Districts" based on the requirement for the state to cover all costs for school building and renovation projects in these districts under the supervision of the New Jersey Schools Development Authority.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The district's nine-member Board of Education is elected at large, with three members up for election on a staggered basis each April to serve three-year terms of office; until 2012, the members of the Board of Education were appointed by the city's mayor.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] As of the 2022–23 school year, the district had 12 schools, an enrollment of 9,690 students, and 777.4 classroom teachers (on an FTE basis), for a student–teacher ratio of 12.5:1.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Schools in the district (with 2022–23 enrollment data from the National Center for Education Statistics) are Lincoln Elementary School (578; K-4), Livingston Elementary School (342; K-5), Lord Stirling Elementary School (490; PreK-5), McKinley Community Elementary School (640; PreK-8), A.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Chester Redshaw Elementary School (784; PreK-5), Paul Robeson Community School For The Arts (665; K-8), Roosevelt Elementary School (609; K-5), Blanquita B.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Valenti Community School (opened 2023-24: 569 in grades 4–8), Woodrow Wilson Elementary School (373; PreK-8), New Brunswick Middle School (1,259; 6–8) and New Brunswick High School (2,477; 9–12).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The community is also served by the Greater Brunswick Charter School, a K–8 charter school serving students from New Brunswick, Edison, Highland Park and Milltown.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] As of the 2021–22 school year, the school had an enrollment of 399 students and 32.5 classroom teachers (on an FTE basis), for a student–teacher ratio of 12.3:1.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] New Brunswick residents also have the option of going to New Brunswick Health Sciences Technology High School, which is a public high school that operates as part of the New Brunswick Public Schools, focused on health sciences.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The Livingston Avenue Historic District is a historic district located along Livingston Avenue between Hale and Morris streets.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The district was added to the National Register of Historic Places on February 16, 1996, for its significance in architecture, social history, and urban history from 1870 to 1929.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The city is crisscrossed a wide range of roads and highways.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] In the city is the intersection of US 1 and Route 18, and is bisected by Route 27.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] New Brunswick hosts less than a mile of the New Jersey Turnpike (Interstate 95).
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] A few turnpike ramps are in the city that lead to Exit 9 which is just outside the city limits in East Brunswick.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Other major roads that are nearby include the Garden State Parkway in Woodbridge Township and Interstate 287 in neighboring Edison, Piscataway and Franklin townships.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The New Brunswick Parking Authority manages 14 ground-level and multi-story parking facilities across the city.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] CitiPark manages a downtown parking facility at 2 Albany Street.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] New Brunswick is served by NJ Transit and Amtrak trains on the Northeast Corridor Line.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] NJ Transit provides frequent service north to New York Penn Station, and south to Trenton, while Amtrak's *Keystone Service* and *Northeast Regional* trains service the New Brunswick Station.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The Jersey Avenue Station is also served by Northeast Corridor trains.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] For other Amtrak connections, riders can take NJ Transit to New York Penn Station, Newark Penn Station, Trenton Transit Center or Metropark.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Local bus service is provided by NJ Transit's 810, 811, 814, 815, and 818 routes.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Also available is the extensive Rutgers Campus bus network.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Middlesex County Area Transit (MCAT) shuttles provide service on routes operating across the county, including the M1 route, which operates between Jamesburg and the New Brunswick station.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] DASH/CAT buses, operated by Somerset County on the 851 and 852 routes connect New Brunswick and Bound Brook.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Suburban Trails offers service to and from New York City on Route 100 between Princeton and the Port Authority Bus Terminal; on Route 500 between New Brunswick and along 42nd Street to the United Nations; and Route 600 between East Windsor and Wall Street in Lower Manhattan.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Studies are being conducted to create the New Brunswick Bus Rapid Transit system.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Intercity bus service from New Brunswick to Columbia, Maryland, and Washington, D.C., is offered by OurBus *Prime*.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] New Brunswick was at the eastern terminus of the Delaware & Raritan Canal, of which there are remnants surviving or rebuilt along the river.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Until 1936, the city was served by the interurban Newark–Trenton Fast Line, which covered a 72-mile (116 km) route that stopped in New Brunswick as it ran between Jersey City and Trenton.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The Raritan River Railroad ran to New Brunswick, but is now defunct along this part of the line.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The track and freight station still remain.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Proposals have been made to use the line as a light rail route that would provide an option for commuters now driving in cars on Route 18.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Old Bridge Airport in Old Bridge supply short-distance flights to surrounding areas and is the closest air transportation services.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The next nearest commercial airports are Princeton Airport located 14 miles (23 km) southwest (about 23 minutes drive); and Newark Liberty International Airport, which serves as a major hub for United Airlines and located 22 miles (35 km) north (about 31 minutes drive) from New Brunswick.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] Saint Peter's University Hospital, Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital, Robert Wood Johnson Medical School, the Cancer Institute of New Jersey, and The Bristol-Myers Squibb Children's Hospital are all located in the city of New Brunswick.
[src:new-brunswick-new-jersey/new-brunswick-new-jersey-p02] The city is aptly named the "Healthcare City" for its wide array of public and private healthcare services.
